                <p>Famous--or infamous, depending on your point of view--English game designer Peter Molyneux has opened up about his <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/articles/peter-molyneux-is-making-his-last-game-i-just-havent-got-the-life-energy-left-to-do-this-again/1100-6535211/" data-ref-id="1100-6535211">forthcoming and reportedly last game ever</a>, <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/games/masters-of-albion/" data-ref-id="5000-640432">Masters of Albion</a>, calling it a "redemption title" for all the years that he overpromised and underdelivered.</p><p>In an Edge interview (<a href="https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/its-about-redemption-peter-molyneux-says-masters-of-albion-will-make-up-for-decades-of-overpromising-on-things/" data-target="true" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">via VGC</a>), Molyneux said that promising his games will do A, B, and C has always led him into trouble when those promises never came to fruition, citing his previous projects like the God game <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/games/black-and-white/" data-ref-id="5000-2614">Black &amp; White</a> and the RTS <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/games/dungeon-keeper/" data-ref-id="5000-850">Dungeon Keeper</a>.</p>



    
